The idea with which the poet intends to conclude his epistle is this, that he alone is happy who regulates his life by the maxims of wisdom. In order to express this, he adopts the language which the Stoics of the day were fond of using in reference to the superior privileges of their wise man. As the Stoics, however, carried their notions of their wise man to a ridiculous length, it is easy to per- ceive that Horace, though he embraced what was good in the philoso— phical tenets of ,this sect, could not give in to their ridiculous paradoxeS. Hence the piece of raillery with which the epistle terminantes—108. Praecipue scmus, διο. The Stoics regarded a sound and healthy frame as among the many advantages which their discipline conferred. But after alluding to this, the poet sarcastically adds, m'si quum pituita molesta est ; meaning to imply, that there were occasions when the wise man of the Stoics was brought down to the level of the common herd. In order to comprehend the full force of the raillery here employed, we must bear in mind, that they who labour under any defluxion of phlegm experience at the same time a dulness in the senses of smell and taste 3 and that this, applied in a figurative sense to the intellect, couveys the idea of an unfitness for any subtle examination of things,

or any nice exercise of judgment. Hence it will be perceived, that ’
